 Plan: Consolidation Moments — Surprise-Gated Memory Buffering

 Context

 Currently, every conversation turn extracts facts and immediately injects them into MEMIT weights (chat.py:_memit_inject). This is
 biologically implausible — humans don't write to long-term memory after every sentence. Instead, facts accumulate in short-term
 memory (hippocampal buffer) and are consolidated into long-term storage when something important happens or during sleep.

 This change introduces a volatile fact buffer between extraction and MEMIT injection, gated by a surprise signal inspired by TITANS.
 The buffer is intentionally fragile — a crash before consolidation loses those facts (retrograde amnesia analogy).

 New Memory Flow

 BEFORE:  Extract → Deduplicate → inject_fact() per triple → weights modified immediately
 AFTER:   Extract → Deduplicate → FactBuffer.add()  [volatile, no weight changes]
                                        ↓
                               SurpriseEstimator.evaluate()
                                        ↓
                            surprise ≥ threshold? ──YES──→ buffer.consolidate()
                                        ↓                  → inject_facts(batch)
                                       NO                   → buffer.clear()
                                        ↓
                                  facts stay in buffer (vulnerable to loss)

 Three-tier memory now:
 - Tier 0: Context window (working memory, instant, volatile)
 - Tier 1: Fact buffer (short-term, volatile, accumulated between consolidation moments)
 - Tier 2: MEMIT edits (medium-term, persistent, written at consolidation moments)
 - Tier 3: LoRA fusion (long-term, persistent, written during sleep)

 New Files

 1. src/wake/fact_buffer.py — FactBuffer

 Volatile in-memory accumulator. Never persists to disk.

 - add(triple, turn, surprise) — append fact to buffer
 - consolidate(reason) — batch-inject all buffered facts via memit_engine.inject_facts(batch), clear buffer
 - clear() — discard all (amnesia)
 - size, is_empty, get_triples(), to_dict()
 - BufferedFact dataclass wrapping FactTriple with timestamp/turn/surprise metadata
 - Overflow policy (configurable): "consolidate" (force flush) or "drop_oldest" (FIFO eviction)

 2. src/wake/surprise.py — SurpriseEstimator

 Composite surprise score from three signals:

 ┌──────────────────┬────────┬───────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
 │      Signal      │ Weight │   Cost    │                                  What it detects                                   │
 ├──────────────────┼────────┼───────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
 │ Fact novelty     │ 0.5    │ Free      │ New facts surviving deduplication (count + ratio)                                  │
 ├──────────────────┼────────┼───────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
 │ Explicit markers │ 0.3    │ Free      │ Corrections ("actually..."), emphasis ("remember this"), updates ("I moved to...") │
 ├──────────────────┼────────┼───────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
 │ PPL surprise     │ 0.2    │ Expensive │ Model's prediction error on user input (EMA-normalized)                            │
 └──────────────────┴────────┴───────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

 PPL component is off by default (costs a forward pass per turn on 8GB device). Novelty + markers alone provide strong signal at zero
 cost.

 - evaluate(user_message, new_triples, total_extracted) → float [0,1]
 - should_consolidate(score) → bool (score ≥ threshold)

